I walked in and waited for the hostess. About 3 minutes later, 3 more people walked in and stood behind me. After about 5 minutes the hostess walked up and asked if anyone was waiting to be seated, I said that I was. The people behind me also said they were waiting as well. He looked at them and asked who was first- I am clearly standing in front so I said that was. He looked at the male and asked again and not until he confirmed that I was there before them that he believed me.  As for the food: In my opinion, I’ve had better at the corner Chinese carry out. I ordered beef spring rolls, the pan fried dumplings and the combination Lo Mein. The spring rolls had no beef but were tasty. The dumplings and the Lo Mein had no flavor.

I am writing this review very sincerely. For more broadcasting purpose, I am writing in both English and Chinese. As my first dinner in DC, this restaurant is a nightmare for our visitors. I took my parents to visit DC and this is the first restaurant I let them try. However, the service was so bad that they were almost very mean to us. They way they look at us and they talk with us is like that they look down upon us. I am not a general sensitive person. And I don’t care so much about people’s attitudes. But the people in this restaurant, they really gave me a very bad bad experience about how we are unwelcome by those people who speak the same language as us. At first, I thought this is the way how the capital people behave. We went to Korean, American, Italy restaurant during the rest of the visiting, the service was much much better and we were so pleased to eat at those places. I am very disappointed to have same culture background with those people. Maybe they don’t think so because they seems to treat Americans much better than treat us. I don’t want to raise racial controversy , just describing my personal experience. 我在这家餐馆的经历简直糟糕透了，第一天来到华盛顿，带爸妈吃第一顿中餐弥补一下旅途的劳累，结果整个过程非常不愉快。简直是我在美国这么多年遇到的服务态度最差的饭店，不限国别。他们就像在鄙视我们一样，无论是点菜还是要米饭，都一副高高在上，万分嫌弃的样子。本来想带父母高高兴兴吃顿饭，结果受了一肚子气，还要老老实实给他们付小费，因为小费已经算进帐单里了！我不是一个对别人态度很敏感的人，但是这家店作为我们一家华盛顿初体验，实在是让我们实实在在感受了一番,华盛顿人民是多么的不欢迎我们！虽然同说中文,可能他们并不觉得我们是同胞吧！因为他们对待隔壁桌比我们还晚到的说英语的美国人，态度可是相当的好！我本来以为首都人民都是这样一副样子，结果后来几天吃的韩国餐厅，美国餐厅，意大利餐厅，服务态度都非常好，我跟父母吃的非常开心。不想在国别种族上引起争议，只是客观阐述一下个人经历。

Take it from a real Chinese who’s doing this to help those of you who don’t know real Chinese food (Sichuan province in this case.) Skip your usual egg drop, wonton, hot n sour soups, egg rolls, steamed or fried dumplings PLEASE!!! You want that you could’ve just go to any bad takeout joint. Go to the “Chinese Menu” section, ask the waiter/waitress or the manager which protein and vegetables you want, prepared in real Sichuan style, and let them suggest you the choices. Sichuan food is generally spicy and numbing, your taste buds are in for a treat. Enjoy!

EXPECT SPICE: I'm not personally a fan of Chinese cuisine, but even I found this local restaurant worth the $20/person price tag. Sichuan pavilion is a surprisingly authentic taste of China's "spice capitol": Sichuan Province. While I've never been to the Sichuan Province of China, the friends who accompanied me told me that they felt like they were back in the spice capitol when eating.  The dishes are communal, parties order several and then take food from the plate and mix it in their personal rice bowls to eat. A neat social way to dine.
